2. Functions¶

2.1 Objective functions¶

In this section we define the objective functions $f$ and $H$, which are defined in equations (3.1) and (4.1) here. In order to do this, we first define functions for evaluating the optimal transport cost $W_2^2(1,\sum_i v_i \delta_{x_i})$; see equation (4.2) here.

In [3]:
#@title Functions for solving the semi-discrete optimal transport problem

def init_w(x,om):
    """
    This function generates a weight vector w so that the Laguerre tessellation
    of the box om generated by the seeds x and the weights w has cells of
    positive area. It uses the rescaling method from Section 2.2 of the
    following paper:
    J. Meyron. Initialization procedures for discrete and semi-discrete
    optimal transport. Computer-Aided Design, 115:1322, 2019.

    Inputs:
        x  - seeds, (n,2) numpy array
        om - domain, pysdot ConvexPolyhedraAssembly (assumed to be a rectangle)

    Outputs:
        w - weights of the Laguerre diagram, (n,) numpy array

    """

    # Centroid of the rectangular domain
    com = 0.5 * ( om.max_position() + om.min_position() )

    # Width and height of the rectangular domain
    Lx = om.max_position()[0] - om.min_position()[0]
    Ly = om.max_position()[1] - om.min_position()[1]

    # Define a dilation factor l and a translation t so that the transformed
    # seeds X = l*(x-com) + com = l*x + t lie inside the box. We choose to map
    # the 1st seed to the centre of mass (com) of the box. All the other seeds
    # are dilated about the centre of mass so that they lie inside the box.
    alpha = 0.49
    l = alpha * np.min([Lx,Ly]) / np.max(np.abs(x-x[0,:]))
    t = com - l*x[0,:]

    # The corresponding weight w for the original seeds
    # (see Lemma 2.1 in https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871)
    w = -2.*np.sum(t*x,axis=1) - (l-1.)*np.sum(x*x,axis=1)

    return w

def solve_OT_problem(x,v,om):
    """
    This function uses pysdot to solve the semi-discrete optimal transport
    problem with source measure equal to the Lebesgue measure on the domain om
    and target measure equal to \sum_i v_i \delta_{x_i}.

    Inputs:
        x  - seeds, (n,2) numpy array
        v  - areas, (n,) numpy array
        om - domain, pysdot ConvexPolyhedraAssembly (assumed to be a rectangle)

    Outputs:
        w - weights of the Laguerre diagram, (n,) numpy array
        c - centroids of the Laguerre cells, (n,2) numpy array

    """

    # Error tolerance for the OT solver
    err_tol = 1e-3*np.min(v)

    # Generate initial weights such that all cells have positive area
    w0 = init_w(x,om)

    # Initialise the optimal transport problem
    ot = OptimalTransport(positions = x, masses = v, weights = w0, domain = om,
                          obj_max_dm = err_tol, verbosity = 0,
                          linear_solver = 'Scipy')

    # Solve the optimal transport problem
    ot.adjust_weights()

    # Get cell data
    c = ot.get_centroids() # centroids of the cells
    av = ot.pd.integrals() # areas of the cells
    w = ot.get_weights() # weights

    # Difference between the true areas and target areas
    dv = np.max( np.abs(v-av) )

    # Error message if dv > tolerance
    if dv > err_tol:
        print('Maximum error in volume ',dv)
        raise('Volume tolerance not met')

    return w, c

The following function computes the objective function $H$ and its gradient; see equation (4.1) here.

In [4]:
#@title The objective function $H$
def compute_H_dH(x,b,v,om):
    """
    This function evaluates the concave function H defined in equation (4.1) in
    this paper: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871

    Inputs:
        x  - seeds, (n,2) numpy array
        b  - target centroids, (n,2) numpy array
        v  - target areas, (n,) numpy array
        om - domain, pysdot ConvexPolyhedraAssembly (assumed to be a rectangle)

    Outputs:
        H  - value of H, float
        dH - gradient of H, (n,) numpy array

    """

    w, c = solve_OT_problem(x,v,om)

    # Compute H and its gradient (assuming that the seeds are distinct)
    H = np.sum( v*np.sum((b-c)*x, axis=1) )
    dH = v.reshape(-1,1)*(b-c)

    return H, dH

The following functions compute the objective function $f$; see equation (3.1) here.

In [5]:
#@title The objective function $f$ (least squares error)

def normalisation(vol,n):
    return (vol ** 3)/(n ** 2)

def compute_F(x,b,v,om):
    """
    This function evaluates the normalised least squares error defined
    in equation (5.2) in this paper: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871

    Input:
        x  - seeds, (n,2) numpy array
        b  - target centroids, (n,2) numpy array
        v  - target areas, (n,) numpy array
        om - domain, pysdot ConvexPolyhedraAssembly (assumed to be a rectangle)

    Output:
        f  - value of f (normalised), float
    """

    w, c = solve_OT_problem(x,v,om)

    #  Compute f
    f  =  (np.linalg.norm(v.reshape(-1,1)*(b-c)) ** 2) / normalisation(om.measure(),v.size)

    return f

2.2. Constraint functions¶

First we define the constraint functions $c_{ij}$, which are defined in Section 5.1 here. The constraint $c_{ij}(\mathbf{X}) \ge 0$ ensures that the distance between the $i$-th and $j$-th seeds is greater than a prescribed tolerance.

In [6]:
#@title Pairwise distance constraint $c_{ij} \ge 0 \; \forall \; i,j$

def pairwise(x,delta):
    """
    This function evaluates the constraint function
    0.5*c_{ij} = 0.5*(|x_i-x_j|^2-delta^2) for each i,j distinct.

    Inputs:
        x - seeds, (n,2) numpy array
        delta - minimum distance between seeds, float

    Outputs:
          - value of the constraint function, (N*(N-1)/2,) numpy array

    """

    tmp = cdist(x,x) # cdist imported from scipy
    indices = np.tril_indices_from(tmp,k=-1)
    pd = np.asarray(tmp[indices])

    return 0.5*(pd**2-delta**2)

def Dpairwise(x):
    """
    Gradient of the constraint function pairwise, i.e., the derivative of
    0.5*(|x_i-x_j|^2-delta^2) with respect to x_k.

    Inputs:
        x - seeds, (n,2) numpy array

    Outputs:
          - gradient of the constraint function, (N*(N-1)/2,N,2) numpy array

    """

    tmp = cdist(x,x)
    n_seeds = np.shape(x)[0]
    indices = np.tril_indices_from(tmp,k=-1)
    pd = np.asarray(tmp[indices])
    n_constraints = np.size(pd)
    J = np.zeros((n_constraints,n_seeds,2))

    for k in range(n_constraints):
        ind0 = indices[0][k];ind1=indices[1][k]
        J[k,ind0,:] = x[ind0,:]-x[ind1,:]
        J[k,ind1,:] = x[ind1,:]-x[ind0,:]

    return J

Now we define the constraint function $c_{\mathrm{ball}}$, which is defined in Section 5.1 here. The constraint $c_{\mathrm{ball}}(\mathbf{X}) \ge 0$ ensures that the the seeds are confined to a compact set.

In [7]:
#@title Ball constraint $c_{\textrm{ball}} \ge 0$

def constraint_ball(x,x0,R):
    """
    This function evaluates the constraint function 0.5(R^2-\sum_i|x_i-x_0|^2).

    Inputs:
        x  - seeds, (n,2) numpy array
        x0 - centre of ball in \mathbb{R}^{2N} is (x0,....,x0), (1,2) numpy array
        R  - radius of ball in \mathbb{R}^{2N}, float

    Outputs:
           - value of the constraint function, float
    """

    return 0.5*(R**2 - np.linalg.norm(x-x0)**2)

def Dconstraint_ball(x,x0):
    """
    Gradient of the constraint function constraint_ball, i.e., the
    derivative of 0.5(R^2-\sum_i|x_i-x_0|^2) with respect to x_k.

    Input:
        x  - seeds, (n,2) numpy array
        x0 - centre of ball in \mathbb{R}^{2N} is (x0,....,x0), (1,2) numpy array

    Output:
           - gradient of the constraint function, (n,2) numpy array
    """

    return x0 - x

2.3 Optimisation routines¶

The following function minimises the least squares error $f$ subject to the constraints $c_{ij} \ge 0$ for all $i,j$. To be precise, it solves the constrained optimisation problem stated in equation (5.2) here.

In [8]:
#@title Function to minimise $f$

def min_F_solver(xinit, b, v, om, d = 1e-3, max_iter = 100, ptol = 1e-2,
                 verbosity = True, table = None):
    """
    This function solves the constrained optimisation problem stated in
    equation (5.2) here: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871
    """

    # Number of seeds
    n = v.size

    # Define the objective function. It takes as input a (2*n,) numpy array.
    objective_fun = lambda x: compute_F(np.reshape(x,(n,2)),b,v,om)

    # Define the constraint function. It takes as input a (2*n,) numpy array.
    scipy_pairwise = lambda x: pairwise(np.reshape(x,(-1,2)),d)

    # Define the gradient of the constraint function.
    def scipy_pairwise_jac(x):
        return np.reshape(Dpairwise(np.reshape(x,(-1,2))),(n*(n-1)//2,2*n))

    pair_con = {'type': 'ineq',
               'fun' : scipy_pairwise,
               'jac' : scipy_pairwise_jac}

    # Calculate ftol based on ptol and the initial value of f.
    Finit = objective_fun(xinit.flatten()) # initial value of objective function
    ftol = Finit*ptol
    print("Intial value of f is", Finit)

    # Formatting the data.
    if table is None:
        # Construct column names
        columns = ["f","MinPairwise"]

        # Creata a pandas dataframe with the column titles above
        table = pandas.DataFrame(columns = columns)

        # Populate the first row of data with initial data
        table.loc[0] = [Finit,np.min(pairwise(xinit,d))]

    # Function to write to the table + print to display on each iteration
    def callbackF(Xi):
        Nit = len(table.index)
        table.loc[Nit] = [objective_fun(Xi),np.min(scipy_pairwise(Xi))]
        if verbosity:
            print(f"{Nit}: f = {table.iloc[-1,0]}, minPairwise={table.iloc[-1,1]}")

    # Solve the optimisation problem using the function scipy.optimize.minimize
    res = minimize(objective_fun, xinit.flatten(), method='SLSQP',
                   constraints = pair_con, callback = callbackF,
                   options = {'ftol': ftol, 'disp': True, 'maxiter': max_iter})

    # Reshape the final iterate into an (n,2) numpy array
    Xf = np.reshape(res.x,(-1,2))

    return table, Xf

The following function maximises $H$ subject to the constraints $c_{ij} \ge 0$ for all $i,j$ and $c_{\mathrm{ball}} \ge 0$. To be precise, it solves the constrained optimisation problem stated in equation (5.1) here.

In [9]:
#@title Function to maximise $H$

def max_H_solver(xinit,b,v,om,R0=1,d=1e-3,max_iter=100,ptol=1e-6,verbosity=True,table = None):
    """
    This function solves the constrained optimisation problem stated in
    equation (5.1) here: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871
    """

    # Number of seeds
    n = v.size

    # Centroid of the box
    x0 = 0.5*(om.max_position()+om.min_position())

    # Define the objective function. It takes as input a (2*n,) numpy array.
    objective_fun = lambda x:-compute_H_dH(np.reshape(x,(n,2)),b,v,om)[0]

    # Define the gradient of the objective function.
    Dobjective_fun = lambda x: -np.reshape(compute_H_dH(np.reshape(x,(n,2)),b,v,om)[1],-1)

    # Define the pairwise constraint function. It takes as input a (2*n,) numpy array.
    scipy_pairwise = lambda x: pairwise(np.reshape(x,(-1,2)),d)

    # Define the gradient of the pairwise constraint function.
    def scipy_pairwise_jac(x):
        return np.reshape(Dpairwise(np.reshape(x,(-1,2))),(n*(n-1)//2,2*n))

    pair_con = {'type': 'ineq',
               'fun' : scipy_pairwise,
               'jac' : scipy_pairwise_jac}

    # Define the ball constraint function. It takes as input a (2*n,) numpy array.
    scipy_constraint_ball = lambda x: constraint_ball(np.reshape(x,(n,2)), x0, R0)

    # Define the gradient of the ball constraint function.
    scipy_constraint_ball_jac = lambda x: np.reshape(Dconstraint_ball(np.reshape(x,(n,2)),x0),(1,-1))

    ball_con = {'type': 'ineq',
                'fun': scipy_constraint_ball,
                'jac': scipy_constraint_ball_jac}

    cons = [pair_con,ball_con]

    # Define the least squares error. It takes as input a (2*n,) numpy array.
    F_fun = lambda x:compute_F(np.reshape(x,(n,2)),b,v,om)

    # Calculate ftol based on ptol and the initial value of H.
    Hinit = -objective_fun(xinit.flatten()) # initial value of H
    Finit=F_fun(xinit.flatten()) # initial value of the least squares error f
    ftol = np.abs(Hinit)*ptol

    print("Intial value of f is", Finit)

    # Formatting the data.
    if table is None:
        # Construct column names
        columns = ["H","f","MinPairwise"]

        # Creata a pandas dataframe with the column titles above
        table = pandas.DataFrame(columns = columns)

        # Populate the first row of data with initial data
        table.loc[0] = [Hinit,Finit,np.min(pairwise(xinit,d))]

    # Function to write to the table + print to display on each iteration
    def callbackF(Xi):
        Nit = len(table.index)
        table.loc[Nit] = [-objective_fun(Xi),F_fun(Xi),np.min(scipy_pairwise(Xi))]
        if verbosity:
            print(f"{Nit}: H={table.iloc[-1,0]}, f = {table.iloc[-1,1]}, minPairwise={table.iloc[-1,2]}")

    # Solve the optimisation problem using the function scipy.optimize.minimize
    res = minimize(objective_fun, xinit.flatten(), method = 'SLSQP',
                   constraints = cons, callback = callbackF,
                   jac = Dobjective_fun,
                   options={'ftol': ftol, 'disp': True,'maxiter': max_iter})

    # Reshape the final iterate into an (n,2) numpy array
    Xf =  np.reshape(res.x,(-1,2))

    return table, Xf

# Function for plotting the objective function f at each iteration of the
# optimisation method
def plot_F(table):
    f,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(4,4))
    ax.semilogy(table.index,table["f"]/table.loc[0,"f"])
    ax.set_xlabel(r"Iteration number")
    ax.set_ylabel(r"$f/f(X_{\mathrm{init}})$")
    return f, ax

# Function for plotting the objective function H at each iteration of the
# optimisation method
def plot_H(table):
    f,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(4,4))
    ax.plot(table.index,table["H"])
    ax.set_xlabel(r"Iteration number")
    ax.set_ylabel(r"$H$")
    return f, ax

# Function for plotting the minimum distance between the seeds at each iteration
# (normalised by the minimum allowed distance delta)
def plot_pairwise(table,dunit):
    f,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(4,4))
    ax.semilogy(table.index,np.sqrt(table['MinPairwise']/dunit**2+1.))
    ax.plot(table.index,np.ones(len(table.index)),'k--')
    ax.set_xlabel(r"Iteration number")
    ax.set_ylabel(r"$\min_{i\neq j}|x_i-x_j|/\delta$")
    return f, ax

# Function for plotting the Laguerre tessellation
def plot_cells(x,w,om,ax):

    pd = PowerDiagram(positions=x,weights=w,domain=om)
    tmpvtkfile = "tmp.vtk";
    pd.display_vtk(tmpvtkfile)

    reader = vtk.vtkUnstructuredGridReader()
    reader.SetFileName(tmpvtkfile)
    reader.Update()
    data = reader.GetOutput()

    N = data.GetNumberOfCells()

    numpy_array_of_cells = dsa.WrapDataObject(data).Cells
    numpy_array_of_points = dsa.WrapDataObject(data).Points
    cells = vtk_to_numpy(numpy_array_of_cells)
    verts = vtk_to_numpy(numpy_array_of_points)

    idx = 0
    for k in range(N):
        nv = cells[idx]
        vidx = cells[idx+1:idx+nv+1]
        idx = idx+nv+1
        ax.plot(verts[vidx,0],verts[vidx,1],'k',linewidth=1)

#@title Functions for generating synthetic data

def make_data_compatible(vi,bi,om):
    """
    This function modifies the target areas vi and target centroids bi so
    that they belong to the set $\mathcal{D}_n$ defined in Section 3 of this
    paper: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871

    Inputs:
        vi - initial target areas, (n,) numpy array
        bi - initial target centroids, (n,2) numpy array
        om - domain, pysdot ConvexPolyhedraAssembly (assumed to be a rectangle)

    Outputs:
        vr - target areas, (n,) numpy array
        br - target centroids, (n,2) numpy array

    vi and bi are rescaled so that vr and br satisfy sum(vr)=area(om) and
    and sum(vr*br)=area(om)*com, where com is the centroid of om.

    """

    # First make sure that the target areas sum to the total area of the domain
    total_vol = om.measure() # area of om
    vr = vi*total_vol/vi.sum()

    # Now makes sure that the centroid of the target centroids equals the
    # centroid of the domain
    com = 0.5*(om.max_position()+om.min_position()) # centroid on om
    br = bi + com - np.sum(vr.reshape(-1,1)*bi,axis=0)/total_vol
    return vr, br

def generate_perturbed_voronoi_data(Lx,Ly,n,x_seed=None,p_seed=None,amp=0):
    """
    This function generates synthetic data for the numerical experiments in
    Section 5.1 and 5.2 of the paper https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871
    """

    # Generate the rectangular domain
    om = ConvexPolyhedraAssembly()
    om.add_box([0,0],[Lx,Ly])
    Lmat = np.diag([Lx,Ly])

    # Set the seed for the random number generator
    if x_seed is not None:
        np.random.seed(x_seed)

    # Generate a random collection of seeds
    X0 = np.random.rand(n,2)@Lmat

    # Compute the corresponding Voronoi diagram and the centroids and areas
    # of the Voronoi cells
    pd = PowerDiagram(positions=X0,weights=np.zeros(n),domain=om)
    b = pd.centroids() # centroids of the Voronoi cells
    v = pd.integrals() # areas of the Voronoi cells

    # Perturb the target centroids
    if p_seed is not None:
        np.random.seed(p_seed)
    angles = 2*np.pi*np.random.rand(n,1) # random angles
    unit_vec = np.hstack([np.cos(angles),np.sin(angles)])
    amps = amp*np.random.rand(n,1) # random amplitudes
    perts = unit_vec*amps # random perturbations
    br = b+perts # perturbation of the target centroids

    # Ensure data is compatible
    va, ba = make_data_compatible(v,br,om)

    return va, ba, om, X0

3.2 Numerical experiments from Section 5.2 of https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871¶

In this section we fit a Laguerre tessellation to synthetic area and centroid data that is obtained by perturbing a Voronoi diagram. First we consider a small perturbation (Section 5.2.1 of https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871).

In [14]:
# Code to perform the numerical experiments in Section 5.2.1
# of https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.00871

Lx = 1 # width of the rectangular box
Ly = 1 # height of the rectangular box

n = 20 # number of seeds

x_seed = 999 # seed for the random number generator for the seeds
p_seed=1002 # seed for the random number generator for the perturbations
amp=0.001 # maximum amplitude of the perturbation

# Generate synthetic data by perturbing the centroids of a Voronoi diagram
v, b, om, X0 = generate_perturbed_voronoi_data(Lx, Ly, n, x_seed = x_seed,
                                               p_seed = p_seed, amp = amp)

# Initial guess for the optimisation method
xinit = b # target centroids

# Tolerances for the optimisation method
ptol = 1e-10
d0 = 1e-3 # minimum distance between the seeds
R0 = np.sqrt(Lx*Ly*n)
maxiter = 1000 # maximum number of iterations

# Fit a Laguerre diagram to the data by maximising H
table, Xf = max_H_solver(xinit, b, v, om, R0 = R0, d = d0, max_iter = maxiter,
                         ptol = ptol, verbosity = True, table = None)

EBSD = np.loadtxt("EBSD_data.txt")

# Number of grains
n = np.shape(EBSD)[0]
print('Number of grains =',n)

# Areas of the grains
target_areas = EBSD[:,3]

# Centroids of the grains - we will use these as the seeds
target_centroids = EBSD[:,1:3]

# Area and size of the box
total_area = target_areas.sum()
box_size = np.sqrt(total_area)
print('Box size in microns =',box_size)

# The rectangular domain
OmegaEBSD = ConvexPolyhedraAssembly()
OmegaEBSD.add_box([0,0],[box_size,box_size])

# Ensure that that the target areas sum to the area of the box
target_areas = target_areas*box_size**2/total_area
v, b = make_data_compatible(target_areas,target_centroids,OmegaEBSD)
